 First, we calculate her regular hourly rate for the first 40 hours
 \text{Regular hourly rate} = 10 \text{ hours} \times 40 \text{ hours/hour} = 400 \text{ hours} \times 10 \text{ hours/hour} = 4000 \text{ hours} 

Next, we calculate her overtime pay for the last 5 hours
 \text{Overtime pay} = 1.2 \times 10 \text{ hours} = 12 \text{ hours} 

Now, we add the regular hourly rate and the overtime pay to get her total earnings for the week
 \text{Total earnings} = 4000 \text{ hours} \times 10 \text{ hours/hour} + 12 \text{ hours} = 4000 \text{ hours} \times 10 \text{ hours/hour} + 12 \text{ hours} = 4000 \text{ hours} \times 12 \text{ hours/hour} + 12 \text{ hours} = 48,000 \text{ hours} + 12 \text{ hours} = 48,012 \text{ hours} 

Therefore, Eliza's total earnings for this week are $48,012.

The answer is: $48,012

 We know that Claire makes a 3 egg omelet every morning for breakfast. Since she makes 3 omelets per day, and she eats 1 omelet per day, she will eat 3 omelets in 4 weeks. To find the number of omelets she will eat in 4 weeks, we multiply the number of omelets she makes per day by the number of days in 4 weeks. 

The calculation is as follows \text{Number of omelets eaten in 4 weeks} = 3 \text{ omelets/day} \times 4 \text{ weeks/day} 
 \text{Number of omelets eaten in 4 weeks} = 12 \text{ omelets} 

Therefore, Claire will eat 12 omelets in 4 weeks.

The answer is: 12 omelets

 First, we know that the total amount of water in the two drinks is 15 liters. Since the orange drink is two-thirds water, we can calculate the amount of water in the orange drink as follows
 \text{Amount of water in the orange drink} = 2/3 \times 15 \text{ liters} = 10 \text{ liters} 

Next, we know that the pineapple drink is three-fifths water, so we can calculate the amount of water in the pineapple drink as follows
 \text{Amount of water in the pineapple drink} = 3/5 \times 15 \text{ liters} = 9 \text{ liters} 

Now, we subtract the amount of water in the orange drink from the total amount of water in the two drinks to find the amount of water in the remaining 24 liters
 \text{Amount of water in the remaining 24 liters} = 15 \text{ liters} - 10 \text{ liters} = 5 \text{ liters} 

Therefore, the amount of water in the remaining 24 liters is 5 liters.

The answer is: 5 liters

 First, we know that she can run at a rate of speed four times faster than she can walk, so she can run at 4 miles per hour. Since she can skip at a rate that is half as fast as she can run, we can set up the equation as follows
 \text{Speed when skipping} = \frac{1}{2} \times 4 \text{ miles per hour} = 2 \text{ miles per hour} 

Since she spends one-third of the time running and two-thirds of the time walking, we can set up the equation as follows
 \text{Time spent running} = \frac{1}{3} \times 6 \text{ hours} = 2 \text{ hours} 

 \text{Time spent walking} = \frac{2}{3} \times 6 \text{ hours} = 4 \text{ hours} 

Now, we can calculate the total distance she can travel
 \text{Total distance} = \text{Speed when running} \times \text{Time spent running} + \text{Speed when skipping} \times \text{Time spent skipping} 
 \text{Total distance} = 4 \text{ miles per hour} \times 2 \text{ hours} + 2 \text{ miles per hour} \times 4 \text{ hours} 
 \text{Total distance} = 8 \text{ miles} 

Therefore, she can travel 8 miles in six hours if she spends one-third of the time running and two-thirds of the time walking.
The answer is: 8 miles

 First, we calculate the total cost of the supplies needed for 20 candles. Since there are 10 wicks per candle, and each candle requires 1 pound of beeswax, the total cost of the supplies is 
 \text{Total cost of supplies} = 10 \text{ wicks} \times 1 \text{ pound/candle} \times 20 \text{ candles} 
 \text{Total cost of supplies} = 10 \text{ wicks} \times 1 \text{ pound/candle} \times 20 \text{ candles} 
 \text{Total cost of supplies} = 200 \text{ wicks} \times 1 \text{ pound/candle} 
 \text{Total cost of supplies} = 200 \text{ pounds} \times 1 \text{ pound/candle} 
 \text{Total cost of supplies} = 200 \text{ pounds} \times 10 \text{ cents/candle} 
 \text{Total cost of supplies} = 2000 \text{ cents} 

Next, we calculate the total revenue from selling 20 candles at $2.00 each. The total revenue is 
 \text{Total revenue} = 20 \text{ candles} \times \$2.00/candle 
 \text{Total revenue} = 20 \text{ candles} \times \$2.00 
 \text{Total revenue} = \$40 

Finally, we subtract the total cost of supplies from the total revenue to find the net profit 
 \text{Net profit} = \text{Total revenue} - \text{Total cost of supplies} 
 \text{Net profit} = \$40 - \$2000 
 \text{Net profit} = -\$1950 

Therefore, Charlie's net profit is -$1950.

The answer is: -$1950

