 We know that there are twice as many worker bees as baby bees, and twice as many babies as queens. This means that the total number of bees is 700. Since there are twice as many worker bees as baby bees, we can find the number of worker bees by dividing the total number of bees by 2. 

The calculation is as follows \text{Number of worker bees} = \frac{\text{Total bees}}{2} 
 \text{Number of worker bees} = \frac{700}{2} 
 \text{Number of worker bees} = 350 

Therefore, there are 350 worker bees in the hive.
The answer is: 350

 Since Tim lives 2 miles away from the school and can ride his skateboard at 264 feet per minute, he will take 2 miles at 264 feet per minute. This means he will cover 2 miles in 2 minutes. Since Steve lives 3 miles away from the school and can bike at 440 feet per minute, he will cover 3 miles in 440 feet per minute. This means he will take 3 miles at 440 feet per minute. Since the winner is the one who finishes first, we can set up a comparison equation to find out who will finish first.

 \text{Time taken by Tim} = \frac{\text{Distance covered by Tim}}{\text{Speed}} 
 \text{Time taken by Tim} = \frac{2 \text{ miles}}{264 \text{ feet/min}} 
 \text{Time taken by Tim} = \frac{2 \text{ miles}}{264 \text{ feet/min}} \times 60 \text{ minutes} 
 \text{Time taken by Tim} = 7.5 \text{ minutes} 

 \text{Time taken by Steve} = \frac{\text{Distance covered by Steve}}{\text{Speed}} 
 \text{Time taken by Steve} = \frac{3 \text{ miles}}{440 \text{ feet/min}} 
 \text{Time taken by Steve} = \frac{3 \text{ miles}}{440 \text{ feet/min}} \times 60 \text{ minutes} 
 \text{Time taken by Steve} = 6.8 \text{ minutes} 

Since Tim takes 7.5 minutes to cover 2 miles and Steve takes 6.8 minutes to cover 3 miles, the winner will be waiting for Tim for 7.5 minutes. Therefore, the loser will finish the race before the winner.

The answer is: 7.5 minutes

