 First, we know that Celine used 90 liters of water from the tank. This means the tank initially had 120 liters of water. After using 90 liters, the tank now has 30 liters of water left. Since the rainwater is twice as much as the water used, we can calculate the amount of water in the tank after the rainwater is added.

The amount of water in the tank after the rainwater is added is given by the formula
 \text{Amount of water in the tank after rainwater} = \text{Initial water in the tank} - \text{Water used by Celine} 

Substituting the given values
 \text{Amount of water in the tank after rainwater} = 120 \text{ liters} - 90 \text{ liters} 

 \text{Amount of water in the tank after rainwater} = 30 \text{ liters} 

Therefore, the amount of water in the tank now is 30 liters.
The answer is: 30 liters

